[1]
Date: Sat, 12 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhuanet, 11 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-02/11/content_2569948.htm>

Thailand to kill free-range ducks on alert of bird flu
-----------------------------------------------------
Thailand plans to cull about 2.7 million young free-range ducks [in
an effort] to prevent [further] bird flu outbreak[s] and eradicate
the virus from the kingdom.
The decision made Thursday [10 Feb 2005] was backed by the belief
that ducks were [more resistant] than other fowls and could carry the
disease longer without showing any symptoms of infection.
On the other hand, the nomadic nature of free-range duck farming [may
have exacerbated] the spread of the disease.
"We have found a high rate of the disease in ducks. They are still a
prime cause of the spread," Bangkok Post on Friday quoted deputy
Prime Minister Chaturon Chaisaeng as saying.
Chaturon chairs Thailand's bird flu committee, which oversees the
prevention of the endemic [disease].
Trying to get rid of the virus, the Thai government has earlier moved
more than 1 million adult ducks to closed farms or slaughter houses,
confined 5.5 million ducks to certain areas, and destroyed 4 million
duck eggs.
The latest decision to cull young ducks would be discussed at
Tuesday's cabinet meeting, while the bird flu committee would ask a
5-billion-baht (about 125 million US dollars) mortgage
[reimbursement?] fund for frozen chickens and ducks and the culling.
So far, 2 provinces in northern Thailand and 1 in the central region
are classified as bird flu-stricken areas, while another 28 provinces
are on the watch list.
